
[1]alternate

   ALTERN'ATE, a. [L. alternatus.]

   1. Being by turns; one following the other in succession of time or
   place; hence reciprocal.

   And bid alternate passions fall and rise.

   2. In botany branches and leaves are alternate, when they rise higher
   on opposite sides alternately, come out singly, and follow in gradual
   order.

   Alternate alligation. [See Alligation.]

   Alternate angles, in geometry, the internal angles made by a line
   cutting two parallels, and lying on opposite sides of the cutting line;
   the one below the first parallel, and the other above the second.

   In heraldry, the first and fourth quarters, and the second and third,
   are usually of the same nature, and are called alternate quarters.

       ALTERN'ATE, n. That which happens by turns with something else;
                                vicissitude.
